Gemischte Lie-Ableitungen
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Für die Lie-Ableitungen von
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 entlang
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 erhält man 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{f}h(x)=\D h(x)\cdot f(x)=\left(1,0,0\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
\sin x_{3}\\
\cos x_{3}\\
0
\end{array}\right)=\sin x_{3}
\]

\end_inset

und 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{f}^{2}h(x)=\D L_{f}h(x)\cdot f(x)=\left(0,0,\cos x_{3}\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
\sin x_{3}\\
\cos x_{3}\\
0
\end{array}\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset

Aus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{g}h(x)=\D h(x)\cdot g(x)=\left(1,0,0\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
1
\end{array}\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

folgt unmittelbar 
\begin_inset Formula $\D L_{g}h(x)=(0,0,0)$
\end_inset

 und somit 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{f}L_{g}h(x)=\D L_{g}h(x)\cdot f(x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Aus 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{f}h$
\end_inset

 bestimmt man die andere gemischte Lie-Ableitung: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{g}L_{f}h(x)=\D L_{f}h(x)\cdot g(x)=(0,0,\cos x_{3})\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
1
\end{array}\right)=\cos x_{3}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Aussagen über Distributionen bzw.
 Annihilatoren
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Wir zeigen den Beweis von Gl.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Annihilator-Summe"

\end_inset

, d.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

h.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Delta_{1}+\Delta_{2})^{\perp}=\Delta_{1}^{\perp}\cap\Delta_{2}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Gln.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Annihilator-Subseteq"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Annihilator-Schnitt"

\end_inset

 lassen sich in ähnlicher Weise verifizieren.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hinreichend
\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset

 Sei 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in(\Delta_{1}+\Delta_{2})^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, d.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

h.
 für alle 
\begin_inset Formula $f=f_{1}+f_{2}$
\end_inset

 mit 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\in\Delta_{1}$
\end_inset

 und 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}\in\Delta_{2}$
\end_inset

 gilt 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \omega,f\right\rangle =\left\langle \omega,f_{1}+f_{2}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

.
 Da der Nullvektor in jedem Vektorraum vorhanden sein muss, folgt für 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 sofort 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \omega,f_{2}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 bzw.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Delta_{2}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 und für 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 in gleicher Weise 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \omega,f_{1}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 bzw.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Delta_{1}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Mit 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Delta_{1}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 und 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Delta_{2}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 gilt 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Delta_{1}^{\perp}\cap\Delta_{2}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
notwendig
\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset

 Sei 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Delta_{1}^{\perp}\cap\Delta_{2}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, also 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Delta_{1}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 und 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Delta_{2}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Für 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\in\Delta_{1}$
\end_inset

 und 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}\in\Delta_{2}$
\end_inset

 gilt somit 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \omega,f_{1}\right\rangle =\text{0}$
\end_inset

 und 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \omega,f_{2}\right\rangle =\text{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Ein beliebiges Vektorfeld 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Delta_{1}+\Delta_{2}$
\end_inset

 kann zerlegt werden in 
\begin_inset Formula $f=f_{1}+f_{2}$
\end_inset

 mit 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\in\Delta_{1}$
\end_inset

 und 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}\in\Delta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Dann gilt 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \omega,f\right\rangle =\left\langle \omega,f_{1}+f_{2}\right\rangle =\left\langle \omega,f_{1}\right\rangle +\left\langle \omega,f_{2}\right\rangle =0+0=0,
\]

\end_inset

also 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in(\Delta_{1}+\Delta_{2})^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Beschreibung durch Basis
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Die Distribution kann folgendermaßen dargestellt werden: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta(x)=\spann\left\{ f_{1}(x),f_{2}(x)\right\} =\im\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -x_{1}^{2}\\
1 & 1\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right)\label{eq:ex-diff-geo-im}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Die 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

-Teilmatrix ist wegen 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -x_{1}^{2}\\
1 & 1
\end{array}\right)=1+x_{1}^{2}>0
\]

\end_inset

regulär.
 Damit gilt 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim\Delta(x)=2$
\end_inset

 für alle 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\R^{3}$
\end_inset

, so dass die Distribution auch regulär ist.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Wir fassen die Vektorfelder spaltenweise zu einer Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(x)=\left(f_{1}(x),f_{2}(x),f(x)\right)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & -x_{1}^{2} & 1\\
1 & 1 & x_{2}\\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

zusammen.
 Aus 
\begin_inset Formula $\rank\,F(x)=2$
\end_inset

 folgt, dass das Vektorfeld
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in der linearen Hülle der Vektorfelder 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},f_{2}$
\end_inset

 liegt, d.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

h.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 Zur Bestimmung der Koeffizienten 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2}:\R^{3}\to\R$
\end_inset

 (Skalarfelder), die das Vektorfeldes
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 bezüglich der die Distribution aufspannenden Vektorfelder 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},f_{2}$
\end_inset

 beschreiben, ist das lineare Gleichungssystem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\alpha_{1}(x)f_{1}(x)+\alpha_{2}(x)f_{2}(x)
\]

\end_inset

zu lösen.
 Man erhält 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}(x)=\frac{x_{1}^{2}x_{2}+1}{1+x_{1}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 und 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}(x)=\frac{x_{2}+1}{1+x_{1}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Die Nullzeile in der in Gl.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ex-diff-geo-im"

\end_inset

 angegebenen Matrix impliziert 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{\perp}(x)=\spann\left\{ \left(0,0,1\right)\right\} =\spann\left\{ \D x_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kodistributionen und Annihilator
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Die die Kodistributionen 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 und 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 aufspannenden Kovektorfelder sind linear unabhängig.
 Die dabei aufgespannten Teilräume haben somit nur den Null(ko)vektor gemeinsam,
 d.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

h.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}\cap\Omega_{2}=\spann\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Da in der Beschreibung von 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 und 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 nur die ersten zwei Elemente der kanonischen Basis auftreten, kann die
 Summe zu 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\Omega_{1}+\Omega_{2}=\spann\left\{ \d x_{1},\d x_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 vereinfacht werden.
 Annihilator 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{\perp}=\spann\{\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{3}}\}$
\end_inset

 ist eine Distribution, die von dem dritten Basiselement des Primal\SpecialChar softhyphen
raums
 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{3}$
\end_inset

 aufgespannt wird.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Involutiver Abschluss
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Die von den Vektorfeldern
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 und
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 aufgespannte Distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\spann\{f_{1},f_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 ist nicht involutiv.
 Mit der Lie-Klammer 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3}:=[f_{1},f_{2}]=-\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{3}}$
\end_inset

 aufgespannte Distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\spann\{f_{1},f_{2},f_{3}\}$
\end_inset

 ist ebenfalls noch nicht involutiv.
 Erst durch Hinzunahme von 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{4}:=[f_{1},f_{3}]=\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{4}}$
\end_inset

 erhält man eine 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

-dimensionale involutive Distribution, d.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

h.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\inv(\Delta)=\spann\{f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4}\}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{maxima}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "Involutiv_Closure_Linear_Konstant.tex"

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{maxima}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Differentialform
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Zunächst überprüfen wir, ob die Differentialform
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 selber geschlossen ist.
 Dazu bildet man die äußere Ableitung:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\d\omega(x) & = & -\frac{\partial\cos x_{3}}{\partial x_{3}}\d x_{3}\wedge\d x_{1}+\frac{\partial\sin x_{3}}{\partial x_{3}}\d x_{3}\wedge\d x_{2}\\
 & = & \sin x_{3}\d x_{3}\wedge\d x_{1}+\cos x_{3}\d x_{3}\wedge\d x_{2}\\
 & = & -\sin x_{3}\d x_{1}\wedge\d x_{3}-\cos x_{3}\d x_{2}\wedge\d x_{3}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Wegen 
\begin_inset Formula $\d\omega\neq0$
\end_inset

 ist die Differentialform
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 nicht geschlossen und damit nicht exakt.
 Die Existenz eines integrierenden Faktors prüfen wir auf Basis von Korollar
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cor:frobenius-integrierender-faktor"

\end_inset

.
 Wegen 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\d\omega\wedge\omega & = & \left(-\sin x_{3}\d x_{1}\wedge\d x_{3}-\cos x_{3}\d x_{2}\wedge\d x_{3}\right)\wedge\left(-\cos x_{3}\d x_{1}+\sin x_{3}\d x_{2}\right)\\
 & = & -\sin x_{3}\d x_{1}\wedge\d x_{3}\wedge\sin x_{3}\d x_{2}-\cos x_{3}\d x_{2}\wedge\d x_{3}\wedge(-\cos x_{3}\d x_{1})\\
 & = & -\sin^{2}x_{3}\d x_{1}\wedge\d x_{3}\wedge\d x_{2}+\cos^{2}x_{3}\d x_{2}\wedge\d x_{3}\wedge\d x_{1}\\
 & = & \sin^{2}x_{3}\d x_{1}\wedge\d x_{2}\wedge\d x_{3}+\cos^{2}x_{3}\d x_{1}\wedge\d x_{2}\wedge\d x_{3}\\
 & = & \d x_{1}\wedge\d x_{2}\wedge\d x_{3}\neq0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

existiert auch kein integrierender Faktor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{loesung}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

